legem iussisse. This was the technical term for the passing of a bill by the whole body of the Roman people assembled in the Comitia. The bill was proposed to the people by the presiding magistrate, in the formula Velitis iubentia, Quirite-s? the people either accepted (iubere) or rejected it (antiquare). In submitting a measure to the Comitia the magistrate was said rogare Zeyem, and the bill was called royatio, and if passed it became a leae; (though this distinction is not always kept).

C. is here speaking of the statues and other works of art which adorned the public buildings of the city in eontrast with those of which Verres and other provincial governors had plundered the allies for the embellishment of their own country houses.
